    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"724904\">rzeta0</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/help.20finding.20right.20version.20of.20lemma.20a.3Cb.20.3D.3E.20a.2B1.20.3C.3D.20b/near/486473553\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Thanks Daniel.</p>\n<p>I had a thought, since the Integers are a superset of the Naturals, are lemmas for naturals applicable to integers in all cases?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>No. Do you mean the contrary? For natural n, if n != 0, then n &gt; 0, which is not true for integers. For the contrary, if no quantifiers are involved, you can coerce them into integers to use the versions for integers.</p>",
